    <h1>Other fes&#xAD;ti&#xAD;val high&#xAD;lights</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201027/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-27"><time>2020-10-27</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | BOOKS</span>
        - <span role="byline">&#x2022; Books by the speak&#xAD;ers and more are avail&#xAD;able at the on&#xAD;line fes&#xAD;ti&#xAD;val book&#xAD;store at swf&#xAD;books.com. For more de&#xAD;tails, go to www.sin&#xAD;ga&#xAD;porewrit&#xAD;ers&#xAD;fes&#xAD;ti&#xAD;val.com</span>
    </section>

    <p>Where: Sis­tic Live, swf2020-live.sis­tic.com Ad­mis­sion: Fes­ti­val pass, $20 from Sis­tic</p>
    <p>IN CON­VER­SA­TION WITH: MAR­GARET AT­WOOD</p>
    <p>The Cana­dian grande dame of dystopian fic­tion, author of The Hand­maid’s Tale (1985) and its Booker Prize-win­ning se­quel The Tes­ta­ments (2019), speaks with Sin­ga­porean nov­el­ist Balli Kaur Jaswal about fic­tion as wit­ness and re­sis­tance.</p>
    <p>When: Next Tues­day, 9 to 10.30pm</p>
    <p>Info: Live ses­sion in­clud­ing Q&A</p>
    <p>TRACY K. SMITH: THE BODY OF DE­SIRE IN PO­ETRY</p>
    <p>The for­mer United States poet lau­re­ate and Pulitzer Prize win­ner be­hind col­lec­tions such as Life On Mars (2011) and Wade In The Wa­ter (2018) dis­cusses her craft and vi­sion.</p>
    <p>When: Satur­day, 10 to 11.30am</p>
    <p>Info: Pre-recorded ses­sion, live Q&A in the last 30 min­utes</p>
    <p>LIU CIXIN: THE POS­SI­BIL­I­TIES OF SCI­ENCE AND IMAG­I­NA­TION</p>
    <p>Chi­nese sci­ence-fic­tion pioneer Liu, the author of the Re­mem­brance Of Earth’s Past tril­ogy, in­clud­ing the Hugo Award-win­ning novel The Three Body Prob­lem (2008), speaks about his work.</p>
    <p>When: Satur­day, noon to 1pm</p>
    <p>Info: Live ses­sion in Man­darin. English sub­ti­tles will be avail­able on video-on-de­mand re­play</p>
    <p>ART SPIEGELMAN: SE­RI­OUS LAUGH­TER</p>
    <p>The Amer­i­can cartoonist be­hind the sem­i­nal Holo­caust graphic novel Maus (1980 to 1991) weighs in on how comics can use lev­ity to ad­dress se­ri­ous top­ics.</p>
    <p>When: Pre-recorded ses­sion on Satur­day, 8.30 to 9.30pm; live Q&A ses­sion on Nov 6, 10 to 10.30pm</p>
    <p>SARAH LEWIS & TEJU COLE: IN CON­VER­SA­TION</p>
    <p>Nige­rian-Amer­i­can writer, pho­tog­ra­pher and critic Cole, whose works in­clude the novel Open City (2011), speaks with art his­to­rian Lewis, author of best-selling book The Rise (2014).</p>
    <p>When: Mon­day, 9 to 10pm</p>
    <p>Info: Pre-recorded ses­sion</p>
    <p>A (TEENAGE) LOVE AF­FAIR</p>
    <p>Young adult nov­el­ists in­clud­ing best-selling Amer­i­can author Cas­san­dra Clare of The Mor­tal In­stru­ments fan­tasy series (2007 to 2014), Aus­tralian Amie Kauf­man and Sin­ga­porean Anit­tha Than­a­balan dis­cuss ro­mance in fic­tion in this Youth Fringe panel.</p>
    <p>When: Next Tues­day, 6.30 to 7.30pm</p>
    <p>Info: Pre-recorded ses­sion</p>
    <p>NAOMI KLEIN: CLAR­ION CALL</p>
    <p>The Cana­dian jour­nal­ist and ac­tivist be­hind eco­nomic and en­vi­ron­men­tal books such as No Logo (1999) and On Fire (2019) speaks about call­ing for change.</p>
    <p>When: Nov 4, 9 to 10.30pm</p>
    <p>Info: Pre-recorded ses­sion</p>


